A protocol idea brewed while spending the coffee breaks at conferences in the queue before a very fancy but slow coffee machine

Coffee.AI: Making addictions and idle time in queues productive again

1. A coffee machine with a touchscreen showing you different types of coffee. If you want a coffee/latte/... you first have to solve several captchas with pictures of types of coffee or other drinks, where you have to point out a coffee/latte/... You only get what you want when you point out your choice consistently.
Variation 1.b with annotating pictures: you get a picture and have to draw the outline of the coffee cups and label the type of coffee
Variation 1.c with military battle pictures: Do first something useful and train our military AI (or terrorist, as all my images are from the Houthis) by drawing an outline around or recognize all tanks, armoured cars, machine guns. 
2. Make this an app in order to virtualize the queue before the coffee machine. Solving the task gives a QR code to scan at the coffee machine.
3. Coffee Waze: for big conferences with a small amount of coffee machines - using the app a count of the queue length is made and you get sent to the coffee machine with the smallest queue.
The queues get partially masked by giving people more tasks to solve according to their spot in the queue.
One coffee machine, deliberately slow and running out of water regularly, is left for the people who do not want to use the app.
4. If you give your personal data, you get faster access to the coffee machine. For example: Put a picture of yourself with a coffee on Instagram, ... and you get faster access / You can also buy priority boarding
5. Make it a social network -> Hi, you did have a coffee together at ... with ... Do you want to stay connected?
6. The artistic business model: Everyone who want to exhibit this piece of art, has to sign a contract which gives us a monopoly on the coffee sales at the event.

Q&A: 
- link with digital rights? We can write a fancy license for the app with which you give all your data away in a fully legal manner.
- Is this ethical? Well, as ethical as capitalism generally is. We steal your data and time, but the coffee can be fair trade.
